subSection.paragraph:
Although the mechanosensation might be the earliest among all the senses ( Naitoh & Eckert, 1969 ), the molecular properties of some mechanosensitive ion channels and their related structures is yet to be determined. A substantial amount of information has been reported for mechanosensitive channels (
Walker et al., 2000
); however, the absence of appropriate preparations to perform experiments at the cell level, difficulty in generation and application of a calibrated mechanical stimulus, polymorphic nature of the mechanosensation, and a limited number of specific pharmacological agents make the functional characterization of novel mechanosensitive ion channels difficult. The presence of a mechanosensitive channel has been reported in various functional studies in crayfishes ( Eyzaguirre & Kuffler, 1955 ; Rydqvist & Purali, 1993 ). There is no information, however, on the genetic and molecular properties of such mechanosensitive channels in the crayfish. A set of mechanically activated channels have been reported in prokaryotes (
Sukharev et al., 1993
). Recent improvements in the field have been achieved and for the first time a eukaryotic ion channel has been shown to be mechanosensitive (
Coste et al., 2010
). The discovered Piezo channels fulfill all the criteria defined for a mechanosensitive ion channel ( Arnadóttir & Chalfie, 2010 ). The mechanical force, developing in the lipid bilayer membrane, specifically drives the channel into an open state ( Haselwandter & Mackinnon, 2018 ). Piezo channels are specifically gated by the force from the lipid bilayer and they are the representative example of a distinct group of mechanosensitive channels. It has been reported that some other type of mechanosensitive channels require additional functional or structural elements for opening, as in the mechanosensor of
Drosophila
and the vertebrate hair cells ( Corey & Hudspeth, 1983 ;
Effertz et al., 2015
;
Zhang et al. 2015
). Protocadherin and cadherin (
Kazmierczak et al., 2007
), transmembrane channel (TMC)-like protein (
Kurima et al., 2002
;
Kawashima et al., 2011
), LHFPL5 (
Longo-Guess et al., 2005
), and TMIE (
Gleason et al., 2009
) constitute a mechano-electrical transducer (MET) complex generating the primary mechanotransduction in the hair cells. An alternative gating mechanism, driven by the force from the filament has been proposed (
Teng et al., 2015
). Although there are some opposing reports, TMC has been proposed as a candidate mechanosensitive ion channel based on gene silencing and structural analysis studies (
Kawashima et al., 2015
;
Fettiplace et al., 2016
;
Jeong et al., 2022
). It has been proposed that an MET complex is necessary for mechanosensitivity in hair cells; however, TMC has been reported to independently function for salt chemosensation in the nematode C aenorhabditis
elegans (
Chatzigeorgiou et al., 2013
)
. Expression of TMC in heterologous cells may retain such a function. TMC genes have been reported in many species such as
C. elegans
as well as in mammals. In crustaceans, however, out of a few genome drafts not much information is yet available for the genetic and structural properties of the TMC genes and related proteins (
Xu et al ., 2021
). We present de novo cloning and structural study of a TMC-like gene and its related protein in the crayfish
Astacus leptodactylus ( Eschscholtz, 1823 )
.

TMC mRNA sequences from neighboring species were aligned to previously assembled transcriptome drafts (
Ergin et al ., 2022
). Primers were designed in reference to the transcript sequence with the highest alignment score ( Smith & Waterman, 1981 ). PCR experiments were conducted to amplify a gene fragment and the obtained product was sequenced for confirmation. Two pairs of nesting primers were designed for a pair of rapid amplification of cDNA ends polymerase chain reaction (RACE) in both directions. We used a commercially available kit (SMARTer 5 ʹ /3 ʹ kit; Clontech, Mountain View, CA, USA ) for the RACE experiments. PCR products were run on gel electrophoresis for evaluation and selected samples were purified by using a kit (QIAquick; Qiagen, Hilden, Germany ). Purified products were sequenced either in a Sanger sequencing or NGS platform (Illumina, San Diego, CA, USA ).

An mScarlet backbone was used in plasmid synthesis. The original plasmid, containing an SCN1A fragment, a gift from Dr. Al George (Northwestern University Feinberg School of Medicine, Chicago, IL, USA ) (see
DeKeyser et al ., 2021
), was modified by substituting the SCN1A fragment by the cloned TMC mRNA. ‘F1_tmc_mScarlet’ and ‘R1_tmc_mScarlet’ primers having matching tails for the plasmid were designed for the In-Fusion assembly reaction. We used NotI and PvuI enzymes to linearize the plasmid and ‘F1_tmc_mScarlet’ and ‘R1_tmc_mScarlet’ primers to amplify the cDNA product. Using In-Fusion HD Cloning Kit (Takara Bio, Shiga , Japan ) the ‘tmc_mScarlet’ plasmid was generated and cloned in E.coli bacterial cultures. HEK293T cells were cultured in a 35 mm Petri dish with high glucose Gibco Dulbecco’s Modified Eagle Medium (Thermo-Fisher Scientific, Waltham, MA, USA ) with 5% fetal bovine serum and kept in an incubator at 37 °C, 5% CO 2. HEK293T cells were transfected with the plasmid using a kit (Lipofectamine 3000, Thermo-Fisher Scientific). Dishes containing cells with a red fluorescent emission were considered as the transfected group. We discarded the culture medium and cells were washed with phosphate buffer saline solution (PBS). The cell solution was replaced with 1 ml PBS (137 mM NaCl, 2.7 mM KCl, 10 mM Na2HPO4, and 1.8 mM KH2PO4). We loaded 1 ml of the calcium indicator dye solution (Fluo-4 AM 2.5 µM in PBS) into the cells by incubation at room temperature for 20 min for a final dye concentration of 1.25 µM. Dishes were positioned under a confocal laser scanning microscope and calcium specific emission signal was recorded in response to mechanical stimulation. Cells were mechanically stimulated by either gently poking with a blunt electrode, pulses of fluid jets, or an osmotic shock. Osmotic shock was induced by increasing NaCl concentration, up to 167 mM, by adding a known volume of concentrated NaCl solution to develop shrinkage. A calcium-specific emission signal from the entire view field was recorded at a continuous 128 × 128 pixel per frame scanning mode at ~4 Hz. Excitation wavelength was 488 nm and a longpass filter of 505 nm was used for collecting the emission. During acquisition, the confocal pinhole was set to a fully open configuration to collect the maximum signal. Designated region of interests (ROIs) encircling either a single transfected or untransfected cell were selected for data extraction from the recorded images. Peak amplitude of the emission signals was measured for calculations and statistical tests. Recordings were baseline corrected and peak amplitudes were compared in MATLAB environment by using a two sample t-test.

We calculated the structure of the cloned channel protein by using different approaches. Firstly, the protein sequence was submitted to I-TASSER platform for calculation of the three-dimensional structure ( Yang & Zhang, 2015 ); I-TASSER platform used the mouse TMEM16A chloride-channel crystallographic structure as the template (
Lam et al., 2022
). An alternative calculation, with some success, was performed in AlphaFold platform (
Jumper et al ., 2021
;
Varadi et al ., 2022
). The best result was obtained in SWISS-MODEL, which is another platform for the structural calculations (
Waterhouse et al., 2018
). The platform used the recently published
C. elegans
tmc-1 single particle cryoelectron microscopy data as the template for calculations (
Jeong et al., 2022
). Figures of the structural calculations were produced in Visual Molecular Dynamics (VMD) platform (
Humphrey et al. , 1996
).

Primers were designed in reference to the previously prepared ganglionic transcriptome draft. Different combinations of the primers resulted in various sizes of gene fragments in PCR experiments. ‘F1_tmc1’ and ‘R1_tmc1’ primers gave products with an approximately 350 base-pairs in size (
Fig. 1A
). Combination of ‘F2_tmc1’ and ‘R1_tmc1’ primers produced a PCR product in size of ~1,000 base pairs (not shown).

The gene fragments were Sanger sequenced. Analysis of the sequence of the translated gene fragments revealed a sequence similar to that of the conserved domain of ‘transmembrane channel like protein’ (

Keresztes 
et al.,
2003

). The identified sequence was used to design new primers to explore the missing parts of the mRNA. ‘F3_tmc1’ and ‘R1_tmc1’ resulted in ~1.6 kbp-long PCR product. This product was sequenced in an NGS platform (Illumina, San Diego, CA, 
USA
). Short reads were 
de novo
assembled into a set of contigs in DNASTAR platform (SeqMan NGen®, Version 17.2; DNASTAR, Madison, WI, 
USA
). The calculated contigs were assembled to the identified gene fragment. The newly assembled sequence (1.6 kbp in size) was used to design the primers ‘tmc_3F’ and ‘tmc_5R’ for the subsequent rapid amplification of cDNA ends, polymerase chain reactions (RACE-PCR) (
Table 1
).

The ORF was translated into a protein sequence of 832 amino acids (GenBank accession number WCO13212). The identified amino acid sequence was compared to a collection of 29 sequences available in several other species. MATLAB environment was used to generate a phylogenetic tree with the Jukes-Cantor distance calculation method. A distinction between TMC1, TMC2, and TMC7 channels was apparent in a graph (
Fig. 2A
). The calculations show a similarity to TMC7 group of channels for the cloned protein. The protein sequence was aligned against the human TMC proteins and an apparent similarity was observed. especially to human TMC7 protein. (
Fig. 2B
).

fluorescence (
Fig. 4A
). The HEK293T tmc_mScarlet-transfected cells were loaded with Fluo-4 AM cell permeant calcium indicator for mechanosensitivity experiments (
Fig. 4B
).

