subSection.paragraph:
The TMC family has received substantial interest for its potential role in mechano-electrical transduction, particularly in the hair cells of the inner ear of vertebrates (

Pan 
et al
., 2013

). Abolishment of mechanosensitivity in the hair cells of TMCknock-out animals is an important finding in support of TMC as a mechanosensitive channel candidate. (
Deol & Kocher, 1958
; 
Steel & Bock, 1980
). Hearing loss observed in human mutants of TMC1 and TMC2 supported the hypothesis (

Kurima 
et al
., 2002

). Observation of similar changes in TMIE protein knockout animals and human mutants, however, has challenged the hypothesis (

Naz 
et al
., 2002

; 

Gleason 
et al
. 2009

; 

Cunningham 
et al
., 2020

). It has been proposed that the mechanical gating process in the hair cells would require a complex structure opposing to that reported in Piezo channels (
Haselwandter & MacKinnon, 2018
). A substantial amount of data conclusively indicates that the TMC protein is among the essential elements of the mechano-electrical transducer complex in the hair cells. A scientific debate nevertheless continues whether the TMC protein can form an independent mechanosensitive channel in the cell membrane (
Fettiplace, 2016
). The mRNA identified in our work was considered most similar to that of the TMC7 channel subgroup. We scanned through the transcriptome drafts, which we assembled in our model animal, and were not able to find any other transcript for a different subgroup of TMC-like gene family. The search for probable presence of any auxiliary proteins for a channel complex yielded no results. We were unable to find any transcript similar to human TMIE or protocadherin-15, and we hypothesize that the cloned TMC-like protein may function differently.

